@prefix dcterms: <http://purl.org/dc/terms/> .
@prefix oc: <https://ontoskills.sh/ontology#> .
@prefix prov: <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#> .
@prefix skos: <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

oc:skill_claude_plugin_official_math_olympiad a oc:DeclarativeSkill,
        oc:Skill ;
    dcterms:identifier "math-olympiad" ;
    skos:broader "Competition math problem solver" ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom "../.agents/skills/anthropics/claude-plugin-official/math-olympiad" ;
    oc:contentHash "84766ffdb312de59ac42d9c26f8d1e4844abd0b13a1127e0c5e45a30bba87acb" ;
    oc:differentia "that uses adversarial multi-agent verification with dual context isolation to catch errors self-verification misses, optimizing for conditional accuracy over coverage" ;
    oc:handlesFailure oc:ComputationTimeout,
        oc:InvalidInput ;
    oc:hasAllowedTool "Bash",
        "Python" ;
    oc:hasArgumentHint "competition math problem statement or proof to verify" ;
    oc:hasCategory "research" ;
    oc:hasDescription "Solve competition math problems (IMO, Putnam, USAMO, AIME) with adversarial verification that catches the errors self-verification misses. Activates when asked to 'solve this IMO problem', 'prove this olympiad inequality', 'verify this competition proof', 'find a counterexample', 'is this proof correct', or for any problem with 'IMO', 'Putnam', 'USAMO', 'olympiad', or 'competition math' in it. Uses pure reasoning (no tools) — then a fresh-context adversarial verifier attacks the proof using specific failure patterns, not generic 'check logic'. Outputs calibrated confidence — will say 'no confident solution' rather than bluff. If LaTeX is available, produces a clean PDF after verification passes." ;
    oc:hasName "math-olympiad" ;
    oc:hasSection [ a oc:Section ;
            oc:hasContent [ a oc:FrontmatterBlock ;
                    oc:blockType "frontmatter" ;
                    oc:contentOrder 1 ;
                    oc:rawYaml """name: math-olympiad
description:
  "Solve competition math problems (IMO, Putnam, USAMO, AIME) with adversarial
  verification that catches the errors self-verification misses. Activates when
  asked to 'solve this IMO problem', 'prove this olympiad inequality', 'verify
  this competition proof', 'find a counterexample', 'is this proof correct', or
  for any problem with 'IMO', 'Putnam', 'USAMO', 'olympiad', or 'competition
  math' in it. Uses pure reasoning (no tools) — then a fresh-context adversarial
  verifier attacks the proof using specific failure patterns, not generic 'check
  logic'. Outputs calibrated confidence — will say 'no confident solution'
  rather than bluff. If LaTeX is available, produces a clean PDF after
  verification passes."
version: 0.1.0
""" ] ;
            oc:sectionLevel 0 ;
            oc:sectionOrder 0 ;
            oc:sectionTitle "" ],
        [ a oc:Section ;
            oc:hasSubsection [ a oc:Section ;
                    oc:hasContent [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                            oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                            oc:contentOrder 2 ;
                            oc:textContent """**Tool policy**: Solvers and verifiers use THINKING ONLY in the tight-budget
workflow. Competition math is reasoning. Computation is for deep mode (§6c), and
even then bounded — a recurrence that's doubly-exponential can't be computed
past n~30, work mod 2^m instead.""" ],
                        _:ref_4482bccabea55179 ;
                    oc:sectionLevel 2 ;
                    oc:sectionOrder 2 ;
                    oc:sectionTitle "The five things that change outcomes" ],
                [ a oc:Section ;
                    oc:hasSubsection [ a oc:Section ;
                            oc:hasContent [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 3 ;
                                    oc:textContent "**Pigeonhole early exit**: stop launching verifiers once the outcome is decided." ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 2 ;
                                    oc:textContent """**Asymmetric thresholds**: 4 HOLDS to confirm, 2 HOLE FOUND to refute. Why
asymmetric: one flaky verifier shouldn't kill a correct proof; but two
independent dissents is a real signal.""" ],
                                [ a oc:BulletList ;
                                    oc:blockType "bullet_list" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 4 ;
                                    oc:hasItem [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 2 ;
                                            oc:itemText "4 say HOLDS → confirmed, stop (save the 5th)" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 1 ;
                                            oc:itemText "2 say HOLE FOUND → refuted, stop (save the remaining 3 calls)" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 3 ;
                                            oc:itemText """After 3 verifiers: if 2 HOLDS + 1 HOLE, launch 2 more (outcome undecided). If
3 HOLDS + 0 HOLE, launch 1 more (could still hit 4-1).""" ] ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 1 ;
                                    oc:textContent """Rank solutions by (verdict, verifier confidence). Take the top one. Run up to 5
fresh verifier agents.""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 5 ;
                                    oc:textContent """**Dual context-isolation**: each verifier is blind to (a) the solver's thinking
trace — already stripped in step 3 — AND (b) other verifiers' verdicts. Each
verifier thinks it's the first. No "3 agents already confirmed this" social
proof.""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 6 ;
                                    oc:textContent "**A solver cannot verify its own solution.** Different agent, fresh context." ] ;
                            oc:sectionLevel 3 ;
                            oc:sectionOrder 10 ;
                            oc:sectionTitle "5. Rank and vote-verify (asymmetric + early exit)" ],
                        [ a oc:Section ;
                            oc:hasContent [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 6 ;
                                    oc:textContent """**NO WEB. NO LOOKUP.** Deep mode may use Bash/Python for bounded computation,
but NEVER WebFetch, WebSearch, or any network access. Finding the solution on
AoPS or a blog is not solving the problem — it's cheating on an olympiad, and it
teaches us nothing about the skill's actual capability. Put this at the TOP of
the deep-mode prompt:""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 12 ;
                                    oc:textContent """**Orchestrator self-restraint**: The orchestrator itself must not web-search the
problem "to help" the deep agent. If you're tempted to Fetch an AoPS thread
"just to check the answer," don't — that contaminates the skill's output and
misrepresents its capability.""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 2 ;
                                    oc:textContent "**Deep mode** is a single focused agent with:" ],
                                [ a oc:CodeExample ;
                                    oc:blockType "code_block" ;
                                    oc:codeContent """NO WEB ACCESS. Do not use WebFetch, WebSearch, or any tool that touches the internet. Do not look up this problem, its solution, or related problems. You are solving this yourself — the only allowed computation is local (Bash/Python for mod-k arithmetic, small-case enumeration n≤10, symbolic identity checks). If you invoke a web tool, the proof is void.
""" ;
                                    oc:codeLanguage "" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 7 ;
                                    oc:sourceLocation "lines 292-294" ],
                                [ a oc:BulletList ;
                                    oc:blockType "bullet_list" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 3 ;
                                    oc:hasItem [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 1 ;
                                            oc:itemText "**Unlimited time** — no wall-clock pressure" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 2 ;
                                            oc:itemText """**Targeted computation allowed** — modular arithmetic checks, small-case
enumeration, symbolic verification of identities. NOT exploratory brute force
or unbounded recursion.""" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 3 ;
                                            oc:itemText """**The abstention reason as starting point** — if verifiers found a specific
gap, start there. If solvers never claimed complete, start from what they
partially proved.""" ] ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 1 ;
                                    oc:textContent """The standard workflow is tight-budget: 8 solvers, ~15 min, pure reasoning. When
it abstains, the problem may need more time, not more capability.""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 5 ;
                                    oc:textContent """**What deep mode is NOT**: open-ended exploration, literature search, looking up
solutions, multi-day investigation. That's a different workflow
(`math-research`). Deep mode is still "solve THIS problem yourself" — just
without the clock.""" ],
                                [ a oc:BulletList ;
                                    oc:blockType "bullet_list" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 10 ;
                                    oc:hasItem [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 1 ;
                                            oc:itemText "The problem statement" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 3 ;
                                            oc:itemText "The verifier gap descriptions (what specifically didn't close)" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 2 ;
                                            oc:itemText "The best partial proof from tight-budget solvers" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 4 ;
                                            oc:itemText """The instruction: "NO WEB ACCESS — do not look up this problem or its solution.
Bounded local computation allowed (mod 2^k, small cases n≤10, symbolic
identity checks via Bash/Python only). 60-second computation limit. If n≤10
brute force reveals a pattern the tight-budget solvers missed, that pattern IS
the proof structure.\"""" ] ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 9 ;
                                    oc:textContent """**Step 6d (not optional)**: After any ABSTAIN at the verify stage, automatically
launch one deep-mode agent before writing the abstention into the output. Give
it:""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 11 ;
                                    oc:textContent """The deep agent may find the construction the pure-reasoning solvers couldn't
see. If it also abstains, THEN write the abstention. Do not skip this step —
problems with √n or log n answers are often invisible to pure reasoning because
the optimal structure is the asymmetric one.""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 4 ;
                                    oc:textContent """The archetype: a focused agent that gets the proven-so-far state plus "one case
of Lemma 5 is open" — and finds a 3-line argument the case split was obscuring.
Often under 10 minutes with almost no computation. Deep mode is about giving the
problem sustained attention, not throwing compute at it.""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 8 ;
                                    oc:textContent """**Computation bounds in deep mode** (bug #8 lesson): A6's b\\_{n+1}=2b_n²+b_n+1
is doubly-exponential; b_99 has ~10^{2^98} digits. Never compute such objects
exactly — work in ℤ/2^m, or track only v_p(·), or prove the recursion mod the
quantity you care about. If a computation is running longer than 60 seconds,
it's probably unbounded. Kill it and work symbolically.""" ] ;
                            oc:sectionLevel 3 ;
                            oc:sectionOrder 13 ;
                            oc:sectionTitle "6c. Deep mode (when tight-budget abstains)" ],
                        [ a oc:Section ;
                            oc:hasContent [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 6 ;
                                    oc:textContent """This is also a presentation-pass win: the split-free proof is shorter AND more
general.""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 1 ;
                                    oc:textContent """If a proof splits into cases and one case proves easily but the other resists:
**before grinding through the hard case, ask whether there's a route that makes
the split disappear.**""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 3 ;
                                    oc:textContent """Concrete shape: proving f(n) ≤ cn for a constrained function f, with a case
split on a prime p dividing f(n). One branch closes by index arguments in
(ℤ/p^e)\\*. The other branch resists — same group structure, but the arithmetic
doesn't contradict. The fix: the hypothesis "p | f(n)" plugged back into the
governing equation implies **f(p) = p itself**. Once you have that, a
Fermat+Dirichlet argument kills both branches in three lines. The case split was
a detour — it was splitting on a variable that, under the hypothesis, takes a
known value.""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 4 ;
                                    oc:textContent "Check when stuck on case B:" ],
                                [ a oc:BulletList ;
                                    oc:blockType "bullet_list" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 5 ;
                                    oc:hasItem [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 2 ;
                                            oc:itemText "Is there a different pair (a,b) to plug into the governing equation?" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 3 ;
                                            oc:itemText "Are you proving too much? (A cleaner contradiction needs less machinery.)" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 1 ;
                                            oc:itemText "What does case B's hypothesis imply about f at _other_ inputs?" ] ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 2 ;
                                    oc:textContent """The pattern that saves you: the hard case's very hypothesis often implies
something strong about an _intermediate object_ you haven't looked at. Use that
implication directly instead of the original chain.""" ] ;
                            oc:sectionLevel 3 ;
                            oc:sectionOrder 11 ;
                            oc:sectionTitle "5b. When one case won't close — step back before grinding" ],
                        [ a oc:Section ;
                            oc:hasContent [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 1 ;
                                    oc:textContent "If 3 revise cycles all fail: **stop and admit it.**" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 3 ;
                                    oc:textContent """Do NOT guess. A wrong confident answer is worse than an honest "couldn't solve
it." The metric that matters is CONDITIONAL accuracy — when you say "solved,"
are you right?""" ],
                                [ a oc:CodeExample ;
                                    oc:blockType "code_block" ;
                                    oc:codeContent """**Verdict**: no confident solution

**What was tried**: [approaches]
**What WAS proven**: [any lemma or partial result that survived verification]
**Where it breaks**: [the unfixed hole]
""" ;
                                    oc:codeLanguage "" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 2 ;
                                    oc:sourceLocation "lines 329-335" ] ;
                            oc:sectionLevel 3 ;
                            oc:sectionOrder 14 ;
                            oc:sectionTitle "7. Calibrated abstention" ],
                        [ a oc:Section ;
                            oc:hasContent [ a oc:BulletList ;
                                    oc:blockType "bullet_list" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 3 ;
                                    oc:hasItem [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 3 ;
                                            oc:itemText "Is anything OVERKILL? (constructing a double exponential when linear suffices)" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 2 ;
                                            oc:itemText "Which lemmas should be inlined? Which deserve to stand alone?" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 1 ;
                                            oc:itemText "What's the simplest way to say this?" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 4 ;
                                            oc:itemText "Now that we know the answer, is there a 3-line hindsight proof?" ] ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 4 ;
                                    oc:textContent """Output: LaTeX-formatted proof. If `pdflatex` is available
(`scripts/check_latex.sh` returns 0), also compile to PDF via
`scripts/compile_pdf.sh`.""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 1 ;
                                    oc:textContent """A VERIFIED-CORRECT proof is often not a BEAUTIFUL proof. The order you
discovered it is rarely the best order to present it. Launch a fresh
presentation agent with the verified proof.""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 2 ;
                                    oc:textContent "Load `references/presentation_prompts.md`. The agent asks:" ] ;
                            oc:sectionLevel 3 ;
                            oc:sectionOrder 15 ;
                            oc:sectionTitle "8. Presentation pass (after correctness is established)" ],
                        [ a oc:Section ;
                            oc:hasContent [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 3 ;
                                    oc:textContent "Up to 3 revise cycles. Then re-run the vote on the revised proof." ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 1 ;
                                    oc:textContent """If verification finds a hole: launch a reviser agent. It gets (cleaned
solution + verifier's hole report). STILL no access to the original thinking —
the reviser works from the hole, not by rereading how you got there.""" ],
                                [ a oc:CodeExample ;
                                    oc:blockType "code_block" ;
                                    oc:codeContent """A verifier found this issue in the proof:
[hole report]

Fix the proof. If the hole is fundamental (the approach doesn't work), say so and return **Verdict: no confident solution** with what partial progress remains.

For any step you cannot fully close, mark it inline: [GAP: specific description of what remains]. Gaps in the proof text, not in a separate list — they're greppable and the next reviser knows exactly where to look.
""" ;
                                    oc:codeLanguage "" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 2 ;
                                    oc:sourceLocation "lines 244-251" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 4 ;
                                    oc:textContent """**If pattern #40 fired** (one-line-proof-too-clean), the reviser gets a stronger
brief — the Adversarial Brief template from `references/adversarial_prompts.md`
§7. It forces a binary: "the general lemma is obviously false (here's a 2×2
counterexample) — so either find what's special about THIS case, or find where
the proof breaks." Can't return "looks fine.\"""" ] ;
                            oc:sectionLevel 3 ;
                            oc:sectionOrder 12 ;
                            oc:sectionTitle "6. Revise (if needed)" ],
                        [ a oc:Section ;
                            oc:hasContent [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 1 ;
                                    oc:textContent "Before solving anything, identify the interpretation." ],
                                [ a oc:BlockQuote ;
                                    oc:blockType "blockquote" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 2 ;
                                    oc:quoteContent """Read the problem statement. List 2-3 ways it could be interpreted. For each:
is this reading TRIVIAL? If one reading makes the problem easy and another
makes it hard, the hard one is almost certainly intended. State which
interpretation you're solving and WHY you believe it's the intended one.""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 3 ;
                                    oc:textContent """The Aletheia case study found 50 of 63 "technically correct" solutions were for
the wrong interpretation. Olympiad problems often have a trap easy reading.""" ] ;
                            oc:sectionLevel 3 ;
                            oc:sectionOrder 6 ;
                            oc:sectionTitle "1. Interpretation check (30 seconds, catches 50/63 of one class of errors)" ],
                        [ a oc:Section ;
                            oc:hasContent [ a oc:Table ;
                                    oc:blockType "table" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 3 ;
                                    oc:rowCount 5 ;
                                    oc:tableCaption "`references/adversarial_prompts.md` for the prompts. The key patterns it runs" ;
                                    oc:tableMarkdown """| Pattern | The check                                                                                                                                                          |
| ------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| **#4**  | Does this theorem specialize to a famous object (ζ, quadratic reciprocity, etc.) and prove something open about it? → gap                                          |
| **#18** | Substitute the proof's own intermediate identities into any "remaining gap." Recover the original claim? → tautological                                            |
| **#40** | Is any step a "one-line lemma"? Extract the GENERAL form. Find a 2×2 counterexample. If the general form is false, find what special structure saves THIS instance |
| **#5**  | For each invoked theorem: re-check hypotheses FROM SCRATCH. "Continuous on [0,1]" ≠ "continuous on ℝ"                                                              |
| **#6**  | Any infinite sum "bounded" via a regularized value? Check the boundary — if there's a pole there, the sum diverges                                                 |
""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 1 ;
                                    oc:textContent """For each cleaned solution, launch a fresh verifier agent. **Fresh context**: it
sees only (problem statement + cleaned solution). **No tools.**""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 5 ;
                                    oc:textContent "Verifier returns:" ],
                                [ a oc:CodeExample ;
                                    oc:blockType "code_block" ;
                                    oc:codeContent """**Verdict**: HOLDS | HOLE FOUND | UNCLEAR

**If HOLE FOUND**:
- Location: [quote the problematic step]
- Pattern: [which check fired, or "other"]
- Why it breaks: [specific]
- Fixable?: [yes with X / no, fundamental]
""" ;
                                    oc:codeLanguage "" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 6 ;
                                    oc:sourceLocation "lines 177-185" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 4 ;
                                    oc:textContent "Full pattern list: `references/verifier_patterns.md`" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 2 ;
                                    oc:textContent """The verifier's job is to ATTACK, not grade. Load
`references/adversarial_prompts.md` for the prompts. The key patterns it runs:""" ] ;
                            oc:sectionLevel 3 ;
                            oc:sectionOrder 9 ;
                            oc:sectionTitle "4. Adversarial verify (fresh context, pattern-armed)" ],
                        [ a oc:Section ;
                            oc:hasContent [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 9 ;
                                    oc:textContent """**Retry policy**: If an agent fails or times out, retry once. Transient failures
happen.""" ],
                                [ a oc:CodeExample ;
                                    oc:blockType "code_block" ;
                                    oc:codeContent """**Verdict**: complete solution | partial result | no progress
**Rounds**: [how many verify→correct cycles]
**Method**: [key idea, one paragraph]
**Detailed Solution**: [full step-by-step, every step justified]
**Answer**: [if applicable]
**Self-verification notes**: [what you caught and fixed; remaining concerns]
""" ;
                                    oc:codeLanguage "" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 8 ;
                                    oc:sourceLocation "lines 130-137" ],
                                [ a oc:BulletList ;
                                    oc:blockType "bullet_list" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 6 ;
                                    oc:hasItem [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 7 ;
                                            oc:itemText "Drop a condition — where does it become trivially false?" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 3 ;
                                            oc:itemText "Consider the extremal case" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 1 ;
                                            oc:itemText "Work out small cases (test past n=3)" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 6 ;
                                            oc:itemText "Work backwards" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 2 ;
                                            oc:itemText "Look for an invariant or monovariant" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 8 ;
                                            oc:itemText "Generalize (inventor's paradox — more structure is sometimes easier)" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 4 ;
                                            oc:itemText "Try induction" ],
                                        [ a oc:BulletItem ;
                                            oc:blockType "bullet_item" ;
                                            oc:itemOrder 5 ;
                                            oc:itemText "What symmetries?" ] ],
                                [ a oc:CodeExample ;
                                    oc:blockType "code_block" ;
                                    oc:codeContent """NO COMPUTATION. Do not use Bash, Python, WebSearch, Read, Write, or any tool that runs code or fetches data. Numerical verification is not a proof step. "I computed n=1..10 and the pattern holds" is not a proof.

(If your agent harness requires a StructuredOutput or similar return-mechanism tool call, that is NOT a computation tool — call it to return your answer. The restriction is on tools that DO work, not tools that REPORT work.)

Your internal process (iterate until done):
- Solve: Complete rigorous solution.
- Self-improve: Reread. Fix gaps before a grader sees it.
- Self-verify: Strict grader mode. Every step justified?
- Correct: Fix and re-verify. Up to 5 rounds.
- Stop: Self-verify passes twice clean, OR 5 rounds, OR approach fundamentally wrong.

A correct answer from flawed reasoning is a failure. If incomplete, say so honestly. Never hide gaps.

PROBLEM: <insert the problem statement here>
ANGLE: <insert one starting angle here>
""" ;
                                    oc:codeLanguage "" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 3 ;
                                    oc:sourceLocation "lines 94-110" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 1 ;
                                    oc:textContent """Launch 8-12 attempt agents in parallel. **Each agent internally iterates** —
solve → self-improve → self-verify → correct → repeat. This is the Yang-Huang
structure that achieves 85.7% on IMO: one-shot solving isn't enough; per-attempt
refinement matters.""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 5 ;
                                    oc:textContent "Starting angles (vary across agents — see `references/solver_heuristics.md`):" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                                    oc:contentOrder 2 ;
                                    oc:textContent """**The Agent tool cannot enforce tool restriction.** Subagents get the full tool
set. The only mechanism is the prompt. Use this prompt VERBATIM — do not
summarize, do not synthesize your own:""" ],
                                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
