oc:kn_0d273e7e a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Deep mode computation only" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For doubly-exponential recurrences (e.g., b_{n+1}=2b_n²+b_n+1), never compute exactly — work mod 2^m, track v_p(·), or prove the recursion mod the quantity you care about. Kill any computation running longer than 60 seconds." ;
    oc:hasRationale "b_99 has ~10^{2^98} digits. Exact computation is impossible; symbolic or modular reasoning is the only viable approach." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_141dd60a a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PerformanceProfile ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Resource planning for problem sets" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Tight-budget workflow: 8-12 parallel solvers, ~15 min, pure reasoning. Deep mode: single agent, unlimited time, bounded computation. Model tier scales: Haiku uses more solvers (12) with wider voting (7); Opus uses fewer solvers (4) with 12 dedicated pattern-specific verifiers." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Weaker models compensate with width (more parallel attempts); stronger models invest in depth (targeted adversarial verification). The pigeonhole exit saves verification cost." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_32649101 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When one case proves easily but the other resists" ;
    oc:directiveContent "When stuck on a hard case in a case split, step back and ask whether the split can be eliminated. The hard case's hypothesis often implies something strong about an intermediate object — use that implication directly instead of grinding." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Three lines sometimes do what twelve pages couldn't. The case split may be obscuring a unified argument that's simpler and more general." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_4c364a8b a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When verification repeatedly finds holes" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Calibrated abstention: if revision cycles fail, output 'no confident solution' with partial results rather than guessing. Wrong-and-confident is worse than honest abstain. Optimize conditional accuracy, not coverage." ;
    oc:hasRationale "The metric that matters is conditional accuracy — when you say 'solved,' are you right? A wrong confident answer is worse than an honest 'couldn't solve it.'" ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_5ea7a784 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:SecurityImplication ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Always, especially during deep mode" ;
    oc:directiveContent "The orchestrator itself must not web-search the problem 'to help' any subagent. If tempted to Fetch an AoPS thread 'just to check the answer,' don't — this contaminates output and misrepresents capability." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Orchestrator web access would violate the same integrity constraint as subagent web access — the output would no longer reflect genuine problem-solving." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_aa3e5829 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When launching solver subagents in tight-budget workflow" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never allow subagent solvers to use computation tools. The prompt must explicitly forbid Bash, Python, WebSearch, Read, Write and state 'Numerical verification is not a proof step' — use this prompt VERBATIM, do not summarize." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Subagents that write their own prompts and omit tool restrictions will grind Python for 30 iterations and confidently get wrong answers — a pattern that fits n≤10 but fails at n=100 is not a proof." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_aecb1d3b a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PreFlightCheck ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before launching the workflow" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Before solving: (1) check LaTeX availability via scripts/check_latex.sh, (2) identify model tier for solver/verifier count defaults, (3) classify problem type (AIME numeric vs olympiad proof vs verification-only vs presentation-only)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Problem type determines the entire workflow path. Model tier controls parallel solver count, verify passes, and abstention thresholds." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_c9e005f3 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "All modes including deep mode" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never allow web access or solution lookup, even in deep mode. NO WebFetch, WebSearch, or any network access. Finding a solution on AoPS or a blog is not solving — it contaminates the skill's output and misrepresents capability." ;
    oc:hasRationale "The skill measures genuine problem-solving capability. Web lookup is cheating on an olympiad and provides no signal about actual reasoning ability." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_ce172d0b a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before any verification step" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never let a verifier see the solver's thinking trace — it biases toward agreement. Strip all thinking-block content, false starts, and backtracking before verification; provide only problem statement + clean final argument." ;
    oc:hasRationale "A long chain of reasoning reads as supporting evidence even when the conclusion is wrong. The Aletheia case study showed self-verification drops from 85.7% to <5% accuracy under human grading." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_dea7d1a7 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:RecoveryTactic ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When tight-budget workflow abstains" ;
    oc:directiveContent "After any ABSTAIN at verify stage, automatically launch one deep-mode agent before finalizing the abstention. Give it the problem, best partial proof, verifier gap descriptions, and bounded computation permission. Only write the abstention if deep mode also fails." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Problems with √n or log n answers are often invisible to pure reasoning because the optimal structure is asymmetric. Bounded computation can reveal patterns pure reasoning misses." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_f2d736f8 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "During vote-verification step" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use asymmetric voting thresholds: 4 HOLDS to confirm a proof, only 2 HOLE FOUND to refute. Each verifier is blind to both the solver's thinking trace AND other verifiers' verdicts — dual context isolation." ;
    oc:hasRationale "One flaky verifier shouldn't kill a correct proof, but two independent dissents is a real signal. Social proof ('3 agents already confirmed') biases toward agreement." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_f32b5565 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "First step of every problem solve" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Interpretation check is mandatory before solving. List 2-3 ways the problem could be interpreted; if one reading makes it trivial and another hard, the hard one is intended. State which interpretation you are solving and why." ;
    oc:hasRationale "50 of 63 'technically correct' solutions in the Aletheia case study were for the wrong interpretation. Olympiad problems often plant an easy misreading as a trap." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_fd0ee92c a oc:Idempotency,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "During vote-verification" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Verification is deterministic in structure but not in outcome — different verifier instances may reach different verdicts on the same proof. The voting mechanism handles this: 4-of-5 confirms, 2-of-5 refutes." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Individual verifiers are noisy (especially Haiku); the ensemble corrects for this. The pigeonhole early exit saves ~30% of verification cost on clear cases." ;
    oc:severityLevel "LOW" .

_:ref_0671a31b43fe370d a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description """**Specification-gaming check first**: explicitly asks "is this the intended
interpretation?" before solving. The #1 failure mode in prior work (50/63
"correct" answers solved the wrong reading).""" ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_4" ;
    oc:stepOrder 4 .

_:ref_0ab88d3488234e1f a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description """**Calibrated abstention**: will say "no confident solution" with partial
results. Optimizes conditional accuracy, not coverage.""" ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_5" ;
    oc:stepOrder 5 .

_:ref_3f955f68d8933c13 a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description """**Say "no confident solution"** — wrong-and-confident is worse than honest
abstain.""" ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_5" ;
    oc:stepOrder 5 .

_:ref_400e5f0a3982dcf3 a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description """**Same gap twice → step back** — the case split may be obscuring a unified
argument. Three lines sometimes does what twelve pages couldn't.""" ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_4" ;
    oc:stepOrder 4 .

_:ref_5f43e9b721a7bed4 a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description """**Pattern-specific attacks**: not "is this correct?" but "does this make the
#40 mistake? the #4 mistake?" Specific beats generic. The 7-category
refutation taxonomy gives the verifier a checklist.""" ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_2" ;
    oc:stepOrder 2 .

_:ref_689d24c05529679e a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description """**Presentation pass**: correctness and elegance are separate steps. The
presentation agent gets the VERIFIED proof and finds the cleanest way to say
it.""" ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_6" ;
    oc:stepOrder 6 .

_:ref_962fb00648443abc a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description """**"Does this prove RH?"** — if your theorem's specialization to ζ is a famous
open problem, you have a gap. Most reliable red flag.""" ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_2" ;
    oc:stepOrder 2 .

_:ref_ba11c0cff152f8ca a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description """**Short proof → extract the general lemma** — try 2×2 counterexamples. If
general form is false, find what's special about THIS instance.""" ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_3" ;
    oc:stepOrder 3 .

_:ref_d83f2d83a1f57448 a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description """**Asymmetric vote + pigeonhole exit**: 4-to-confirm, 2-to-refute. One flaky
verifier doesn't kill a correct proof; two dissents does. Stop launching
verifiers once the outcome is decided — saves ~30% of verification cost on
clear cases.""" ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_3" ;
    oc:stepOrder 3 .

_:ref_e6cdc45a65f6a78b a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description """**Strip thinking before verifying** — a verifier that sees the reasoning is
biased toward agreement. Fresh context, cleaned proof only.""" ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_1" ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

_:ref_ecca37eac9c6f735 a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description """**Dual context isolation**: verifier is blind to (a) the solver's thinking
trace — which biases toward agreement — and (b) other verifiers' verdicts —
social proof also biases. Each verifier thinks it's first.""" ;
    oc:blockType "workflow_step" ;
    oc:stepId "step_1" ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

_:ref_269534020c9b82d4 a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description "Launch fresh adversarial verifier agents per cleaned solution. Each runs pattern-specific attacks (#4, #18, #40, #5, #6) in fresh context with no tools" ;
    oc:expectedOutcome "Verifier verdicts: HOLDS, HOLE FOUND (with location/pattern/fixability), or UNCLEAR" ;
    oc:stepDependsOn _:ref_6e7e91e43a3472aa ;
    oc:stepId "verify" .

_:ref_4482bccabea55179 a oc:Workflow ;
